          "title": "The outpouring of the Spirit — the face no longer hidden",
          "body": "The chapter closes in verse 29 with a promise that functions as the capstone of the entire Gog-Magog oracle and as the theological bridge to the temple vision of chapters 40-48: 'I will not hide My face from them any longer, for I will have poured out My Spirit on the house of Israel.' The hidden face (*satar paneh*) was the covenantal curse-form of the exile — God's favor and presence withdrawn (Deuteronomy 31:17; Isaiah 54:8). The three occurrences in this chapter (vv.23, 24, 29) frame the entire theological arc: twice in the past describing what God did in exile, once in the future — negated — describing what He will never do again. The ground of the 'no longer' is the Spirit's outpouring. This connects directly to Ezekiel 36:26-27 (new heart, new spirit) and 37:14 (the Spirit breathed into the dry bones). The Spirit poured out is the eschatological gift that replaces the hidden face — not merely the absence of punishment but the presence of God Himself indwelling the restored people. The New Testament hears this promise in the Pentecost event (Acts 2:17, citing Joel 2:28-29, which shares this Ezekiel tradition) and in the Pauline doctrine of the Spirit as guarantee of eschatological inheritance (Ephesians 1:13-14). Whether one reads Ezekiel 39's fulfillment as already-partially-realized or entirely future, the theological movement is identical: the hidden face ends; the Spirit descends; the people of God are permanently home."
